swmm

The goal of swmm is to provide a cross-platform interface to the United States Environmental Protection Agency’s Stormwater Management Model (SWMM) (the source for SWMM is also available on GitHub).

Installation

You can install the development version from GitHub with:

# install.packages("remotes")
remotes::install_github("paleolimbot/swmm")

If you can load the package, you’re all set! There is no need to install SWMM (the package contains a copy).

library(swmm)

Running SWMM

Run SWMM using the swmm_run() function and an “.inp” input file.

result <- swmm_run(swmm_example_file("Example8.inp"))
result
#> $inp
#> [1] "/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Versions/3.6/Resources/library/swmm/swmm_examples/Example8.inp"
#> 
#> $rpt
#> [1] "/private/var/folders/bq/2rcjstv90nx1_wrt8d3gqw6m0000gn/T/RtmpUZ9MT3/file115153e4e1ade.rpt"
#> 
#> $out
#> [1] "/private/var/folders/bq/2rcjstv90nx1_wrt8d3gqw6m0000gn/T/RtmpUZ9MT3/file1151579c604c6.out"
#> 
#> $last_error
#> [1] 0
#> 
#> $last_warning
#> [1] 0

You can find out which version of SWMM is included in the package with swmm_version():

swmm_version()
#> [1] "5.1.13"

Reading swmm output

Use the swmm_read_*() functions (highly experimental):

out_file <- result$out

swmm_read_subcatchments(out_file)

To find out which variables there are to choose from (for the purposes of only reading part of the output, which you probably want to do), use swmm_read_variables():

swmm_read_variables(out_file)
#> # A tibble: 432 x 8
#>    element_type type_index variable_index variable variable_name unit 
#>    <chr>             <dbl>          <dbl> <chr>    <chr>         <chr>
